Way to go!!

text: I've never played any of the Warcraft games, but I'm really looking forward to the movie. What really interests me is that the movie's story is told from the perspectives of both the Alliance and the Horde, so basically both sides are the good guys. I've heard that the filmmakers did it that way because, in the games, players can choose which side they want to play as. So, when they watch the movie, they can sympathize with whichever side they play as. I, on the other hand, would probably watch the movie and hope that both sides can come to some kind of peaceful compromise. For those of you who are fans of the games, I'm curious, is there any possibility of that happening?

text: I have mixed feelings about this... I mean for the most part it looks bad ass. But in its current form it also looks very uncanny if you  actually pause to look at it. Right at 0:03, when they show Stormwind, it looks GREAT because of how fast it goes. But if you pause the invididual frames, imo it looks like shit, especially when they show that group of people at the stairs. The green-screen effect is painfully obvious, and the CGI looks very CGI. If you pause at 0:04, it looks like complete shit if you compare the background to the actors.... Even their clothing looks CGI.  Still, I hope they adress this as time goes by and the movie actually comes out. This is still going to be an early trailer really - people were pissed off at how Jurrassic World looked in its first reveal trailer as well as Terminator: Genisys, but both of those movies reportedly looked better once they had actually released.

text: This movie is going to be great and here are 3 simple reasons why is that:  1. It has an incredible story! No good, no bad guys. Orcs vs Humas. They get in war to survive because the real BAD guys are totally different parties. So you will see and know why they fight. This isn't a bullshit story where ONE MAN kills a whole empire, millions of bad guys and saves the world!  2. Something we haven't seen before! Duncan Jones (the director) said this is a mix of LotR and Avatar and they pushed technology to a whole new level just for this movie. You haven't seen a thing in this 15 seconds. I mean i'm not a real fan of Lotr nor Star Wars, but do you guys love those movies because of the graphics? If so, then you shouldn't be even allowed to go into theaters.  3. A hell of a ride! This is a PG-13 movie. Brutal. War. Not a fucking pillow fight! Blizzard directly was involved into the whole process of making this movie and trust me, they are very well aware how the people are going to react if they mess up the story. They know what people want.  A suggestion: before you throw hate, do some research about the movie and its story. You have net and Google, use it smartass!

text: This movie can't suck.  The future of World of Warcraft depends on it!  If the movie sucks, it will fail to gather more subscribers and it will even hinder WoW's remaining subs because no one is going to want to go around in public saying they play World of Warcraft anymore.  Everywhere I go, people are gonna say: "OMG you play that ****ty Warcraft game like that ****ty movie?" and I'm gonna have to always reply back with: "*SIGH* look... the game is better than that movie, okay!"  I don't want to do that!!!  The movie NEEDS to be epic!!!  I hope Blizzard actually got to see the whole movie and judge it for themselves!  If they judge that the movie is horrible, then they need to cancel that thing RIGHT NOW!!!    But you know what?  I'm confident this movie is gonna rock!  I have this gut feeling it's gonna be up to par with Lord of the Rings and The Hobbit!  It has to be!  That's what most non-WoW players are gonna compare to the movie!  LORT and The Hobbit have set a new standard for fantasy movies and the Warcraft movie has to either be equal or even surpass it!

text: To those saying that the dude jumping on a gryphon at the start is Anduin.........  Have you even played the game?  If you meant it as Anduin Lothar, he was described as a veritable behemot of a man in the books and game, not a slender guy like the one jumping on the gryphon. He also was in his later years, was bald, had a long gray beard, and because it bears repeating, he was a giant wall of pure muscle.  If you meant it as Anduin Wrynn....... that makes even less sense because at the first war, *he hadn't even been born yet* :P  I'll admit this teaser looks good, but I'm not too terribly excited about the movie yet. Videogame movies tend to suck. BIG TIME. And I am not aware of any exceptions to that norm (At least in live action, in anime and CGI, there's been quite a few good videogame movies)  Nevertheless, I'll keep an open mind and watch the movie anyways.

text: I fell in love with Warcraft when my family visited a friend's house and a guy was playing Warcraft (I) - Orcs and Humans there on his IBM 486 PC. This was around 1994-95, and I was around 9-10 year old. It was a cold dark night - around winter time - and I was watching the guy playing this game for hours, I was amazed by animation of the fire, by the dark pine forests, the sound effects of the arrows and the hammers while the buildings were under construction, by the voice of the characters "yes my lord", "for the alliance" "job's done", etc. The first two Warcraft games - and its expansions - had a dark, mystical, medieval feeling, you felt the cold steel in your hand, and so on, it was so exciting to explore the dark spots on the map, you did not know what to expect. And there were just a few races in these games, the resolution sucked - compared to the recent games - but it had such a great feeling and gameplay, you felt you were part of a different world, and you ruled this world.   I was a bit naive, but I hoped that if a Warcraft movie ever came out, it could give me this feeling like I felt back 20 years ago, when first met the game. But seeing this trailer, it rather focuses on the expectations of players of World of Warcraft. In spite of this I do hope this movie will be a success because in that case the hope of a movie of my taste won't die.

text: Now do not get me wrong.  I love Warcraft and Blizzard so much that I am pretty much a fanboy.  Yes regardless I will throw my money at it and go see it.  I was just expecting more out of the cgi.  It just doesn't look believable.  It looks as though I will be going to the movies to see a very long WoW cinematic.  When the teaser opened up with the griffin.  i thought I was being trolled at first.  With a really good fan made movie.  As the second srolled by I could see.  Well all the cartoony cgi.  The orcs looks stunted and off.  As if they are not standing on that hill and their shortness looked as though I was looking at a bad technicolor panoramic.  It's hard to immerse ones self if I don't believe the backdrop isn't real.  The two guards standing their look as though their plated helms are so heavy that they are permenantly looking at the ground.  I am really keeping my hopes up for the Blizzcon official trailer.  I am really excited for the movie.  I just expected better out of the cgi.

text: This movie is going to make a lot of cash just because of its name, but the movie itself I'm laying odds on it sucking. And this comes from someone whose been playing Blizzard titles as far back as Warcraft: Orcs and Humans. Personally I think this movie should be in full CGI like Beowulf. Blizzard makes awesome cinematics. Too many limitations on a live action film that can cause its downfall, especially with a fantasy genre. Another issue I have with live action film is the success relies on not only needing a good story, which writers will likely change and the ability of the actors. Some of the best actors have ruined movies that could've been good. Consider the Mists of Pandaria cinematic the human is ripped as fuck, hell the books reference Varian having enough strength to strangle someone one-handed. Live action film isn't going to be reflect what the physical appearance of Humans really look like in the Warcraft Universe. Humans are better represented in the comics too.

text: Funny to see people refering World of WarCraft over and over in the comments, oblivious to the fact that this franchise had 3 games before WoW came out, with their own lore, characters and events.  Yeah sure, WoW made the franchise appeal to a bigger audience, but there was a very devout number of fans committed to WarCraft years before (myself included). You are not going to see any "Leeroy Jenkins" references, or Night Elves, or Arthas, or Illidan, or Tauren, or Undead.  Also the "Alliance" did not exist during the events of the First War, the Alliance of Loarderon was born during the events of WarCraft 2.  This is NOT a "WoW" movie, this is a WarCraft: Orcs and Humans movie.

text: Upon seeing this I think the film will cover the entire war between the Orcs and Humans. If you notice, you see the assault on the Dark Portal - there are humans with guns, which means they've already gone to Khaz Modan by that point and got them off the Dwarves, which means they've already been defeated at Stormwind and fled to Lordaeron. The trees in the distance in the shot with the riders with guns shows swamp-like trees, meaning that's the Swamp of Sorrows, or the Badlands before they were corrupted by the fell energies of the Portal. You also see Orcs in a snowy environment, which is probably them attacking the Dwarves.

text: Omg Stormwind at 0:03 and the Cathedral of Light a second later :O I nearly broke the slider to watch every scene properly, and the only thing I can say is... every single frame is worthy of a desktop wallpaper. Seems like the perfect mixture of what I've always hoped for: the epicness of the Warcraft III cinematics and the cartoonish style from both the RTSs and WoW. Who knows, maybe this is where the youngest WoW players will finally get a taste of what Warcraft glory days were like for us, the guys from the previous generation, who knew the manual for Warcraft I at heart (1994) and still can't forget the unit response voiced by Bill Roper, the original Warcraft game designer... text: First I Love World of Warcraft! However I really don't like that the movie is going to be a Live Action film. The reasons behind this are, the cost and time it takes to make it are far too much and far too long, where as if you had stuck to the Cinematic Animation (like the game trailers) the movie would have taken far less time and money. Next if the movie was in Cinematic fashion there wouldn't be any fears about an Actor getting injured or killed (accidents on set (Harrison Ford, Set of Star wars VII), drunk drivers (Paul Walker, Fast and the Furious 7)) or even just wanting more money to do the next film! (life and people are too unpredictable) Also If you had gone the Cinematic route you could have set it up to see the film from each Factions Point of View, for example 2 movies released at the same time one would show you everything that happens from the Point of View of The Alliance, and the other would show you everything that happens from the Point of View of The Horde! This would have been AMAZING!! Going that route would have not only made double the money because people would have wanted to see both films, it would have attracted old players back, and brought new players in because they would seen the history of World of Warcraft and had the DESIRE to play the game and be part of that World!........................................This is just my opinion!
